  <static seed="41" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicMath/FractionsCalculation/MultiplyThreeFractions30.pg">
    <statement><p>Multiply: <m>\displaystyle{ {{\frac{7}{5}}} \cdot {{\frac{2}{49}}} \cdot {15} }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="11" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{6}{7}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>When we multiply fractions, if there is an integer, we change the integer to a fraction by writing <m>1</m> as its denominator. For example, <m>15 = \frac{15}{1}</m>.</p>
<p>When multiplying with fractions, reduce numerators and denominators if possible. This way, we can avoid dealing with big numbers.</p>
<p>The full computation is:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {{\frac{7}{5}}} \cdot {{\frac{2}{49}}} \cdot {15}
        \amp = {{\frac{7}{5}}} \cdot {{\frac{2}{49}}} \cdot \frac{15}{1} \\
        \amp = \frac{1\cdot7}{1 \cdot5} \cdot \frac{2}{7\cdot7} \cdot \frac{5\cdot3}{1} \\
        \amp = \frac{1}{1} \cdot \frac{2}{7} \cdot \frac{3}{1} \\
        \amp = {{\frac{6}{7}}} \\
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
</solution>
